What makes Tar Pit ideas so hard?  Supply and demand.  Tar pit ideas will have the largest oversupply of startup founders who want to work on them relative to market demand.  If the idea is obvious and sexy, there is probably a large supply of founders who want to work on it.

Tar Pit ideas tend to be consumer ideas.   Tar Pit ideas capture the imagination of founders who have experienced the problems firsthand. You should scratch your own itch, right?  Tar pits are great places to find fossilized remains (failed startups).

A Tar Pit idea is the most dangerous type of startup idea.  Why? Tar Pit ideas are deceiving.  They look like good ideas, but theyâ€™re not (just like how tar pits look like freshwater ponds to thirsty animals but are actually sticky death traps). ğŸ§µ

ğŸ’­ Musing of the day: The battle of creativity  Are you someone full of ideas? Do you think of various projects, startups, problem solvers, and all you want to do is execute on these? All your ideas are 10/10 and amazing, and you're sure that they'll be amazing businesses?   I would say I fall into this boat. I am an extremely creative person, with many thoughts. Everyday I'll think of a new idea, whether it's something completely unheard of, maybe something that adds onto a current business, maybe it's something that is in a niche I've never even touched. My head is extremely clouded in these ideas, and I'm left with the decision of what to do with these ideas. A constant battle of "is it worth my time?"   As I begin to learn more and more, in life and business alike. There's one thing that I've skipped out on for too long: focusing on one venture. Trying to figure out how to make 5 different businesses succeed at one time is simply just not possible (at least for me). Dialing down on one focus is almost indispensable at this point in my life. I've pushed this off for far too long, and now is the time to take action. Struggle is foreordained, but failure is not certain. The power of your work, when focused in one will be so incredibly powerful and your output will show for it.   Do you struggle with this as well?  What have you done to overcome this?

I present a 2,000-character business plan.   The purpose? To have my business idea tested in public & have fun   Let's do it...  The idea: A text-based content agency for Founders/CEOs/execs. You run your business, we run your mini media company on Twitter/Linkedin.   The Thesis: Execs are waking up to the importance of building an audience on social but they don't have the time or skill to create it.   Why?  1) Building an audience is getting more valuable as the internet becomes noisier & the cost of attention is higher.   2) We've seen the tangible value of founders investing in their brand via text:  @SahilBloom: raised a fund, secured a book deal, and owns several businesses @sweatystartup: got majority of investors for his self-storage business @jspujji: got all of his initial customers for Growth Assistant from a tweet thread  3) There's been emphasis placed on short-form video agencies creating TikTok vids, but I believe text-based platforms have been forgotten.   The opportunity? The value of being a mini media company on Twitter/Linkedin is clear yet founders don't maximize it.  Why?  1) Time. Creating content is looked at as a nice to have, not a need to have. Need to have is running your business, setting your strategy, managing your team.  2) Skills. Even if a founder believes deeply in creating content, they donâ€™t necessarily have the skills. 3) Hard to measure. Even if a founder believes in creating content, they view it as an investment that wonâ€™t drive measurable ROI.    The pitch:  - What if you could give founders their time back. AND - What if founders didnâ€™t have to rely on their own skills. AND - What if you could set tangible goals that you can consistently measure your investment against.   An agency that lets founders have the best of both worlds. Building a brand, while building a company.
